Just thought I'd post my fix:
In Rotation.cs, in the function GetT10DivineStormCooldownProbability, replace the line
    if ((minCooldown < integerSwingCountTime) && (integerSwingCountTime < maxCooldown))
with
    if ((minCooldown < (float)integerSwingCountTime) && ((float)integerSwingCountTime < maxCooldown))

roncli,

You would be surprised, floating points are tricky to work with because of the way they work. Floating points are precise for 7 digits, and have a single representation for each (7 digit) number, however, when you work with them, the "trash" decimals are preserved and so two numbers which are the same (in their first 7 digits) might not be equal.
Try the following program, both x and y should be "equal" to 1.005000f:
float x = 1.005f;
float y = 0.00500001f;
y += 1f;
if(x==y) Console.WriteLine("a");
if (x == (float)y) Console.WriteLine("b");
This outputs "b", but not "a".
(I build with VC# 2008 EE in Release mode, Debug mode behaves "as expected" and outputs both "a" and "b").

As for,
"I cannot get it to crash by running the release version of change set 47954 in Visual Studio and loading US-Korialstrasz-Skidhouse from the Armory."
are you sure you are running the release version without debugging (ctrl+f5)?
